WEBVTT

00:04.908 --> 00:06.750
Okay, this is just a sound check. Bob, say 
something. Hello, my name is Bob. How many people

00:09.234 --> 00:13.299
check this door here? Probably like 100. I don't 
know why they can't have it open. Okay, this is Ron

00:16.624 --> 00:25.676
Shorn, and I'm interviewing Bob Havlin at the 
American Astronomical Society Berkeley meeting

00:16.624 --> 00:25.676
on June 6, 1993. So, Bob, for the record, what's 
your full name? Robert James Havlin. How do you

00:31.944 --> 00:32.645
spell that? H-A-V-L-E-N. Where were you born? 
Utica, New York. And when? 1943. A date? Oh yeah,

00:41.157 --> 00:42.218
September 16. How'd you get interested in 
astronomy in the first place? I think it was a Boy

00:46.924 --> 00:51.570
Scout project or a science fair project when I was 
in the sixth or seventh grade. I had to draw some

00:51.590 --> 00:54.394
maps of the night sky and find north. That started 
my desire to look through telescopes and to buy a

00:55.876 --> 01:03.045
telescope and eventually made my own telescope 
and Gradually became more and more in contact with

01:03.751 --> 01:06.715
the astronomical community. I was good at school. 
Where did you go to undergrad school? Went to the

01:10.782 --> 01:11.903
University of Rochester. And when did you 
graduate from there? 1965. And what was your

01:14.948 --> 01:15.769
major? Astrophysics. Did you start out in 
astrophysics? I started out in astrophysics.

01:21.939 --> 01:22.099
Why? Why did I start in astrophysics? Because with 
my middle school and high school experience in

01:24.983 --> 01:31.513
making my own telescope and reading about 
astronomy, I decided that was an area that I wanted

01:32.101 --> 01:34.783
to go into. As a matter of fact, I only applied as an 
undergraduate to Cornell and to the University of

01:34.823 --> 01:47.335
Rochester in New York State because those were the 
only schools that had undergraduate degrees in

01:34.823 --> 01:47.335
astronomy.

01:48.155 --> 01:49.737
Where did you go to grad school and why? I went to the 
University of Arizona because I realized that I

01:50.297 --> 01:59.205
needed to be at a clear sight where I could get into 
astronomy. It had a good national reputation. It

02:01.087 --> 02:02.108
was growing. I applied to the University of 
Michigan and to Harvard. I got accepted at

02:05.479 --> 02:13.807
Michigan, didn't get accepted at Harvard, and 
then Arizona and NASA traineeship and so on. It was

02:13.827 --> 02:19.732
the best decision of my then young life. Because 
the University of Arizona, of course, is right

02:19.752 --> 02:26.537
across the street from Kitt Peak National 
Observatory. So what did you do at Arizona? At

02:29.300 --> 02:31.842
Arizona?

02:32.986 --> 02:42.179
I got interested in x-ray astronomy and optical 
astronomy and no radio astronomy really. And

02:42.840 --> 02:55.479
gradually did a thesis under Bengt Westerlund 
using photographic data and photoelectric data

02:42.840 --> 02:55.479
on Cepheids and OB associations and the 
relationship of them. And when did you get out? Why

02:56.921 --> 02:57.682
did you pick that? Why did I pick that? Was it the 
person or the field? Person, primarily, I think.

03:04.702 --> 03:15.798
It was the ease with which I was able to work with Dr. 
Westerlund and his vast experience in the field of

03:04.702 --> 03:15.798
observational optical astronomy. Of course, I 
was exposed to almost everything there was to be

03:16.659 --> 03:28.577
exposed to back in the late 1960s because of our 
interaction with Kitt Peak National

03:16.659 --> 03:28.577
Observatory. And there were theoreticians 
around. You know, I did fairly well at most of my

03:32.825 --> 03:49.249
courses, but I found

03:32.825 --> 03:49.249
after thinking about what I really wanted to do for 
three or four months, I decided that I wanted to go

03:32.825 --> 03:49.249
into studying Cepheids and OB associations with 
Bank. He had lots of, he was an interesting guy. He

03:51.672 --> 04:01.707
had lots of unreduced observational data to work 
with and was inspirational in helping me decide,

03:51.672 --> 04:01.707
you know, what further observations were to be 
made and so on. I think that's Sort of a typical

04:03.385 --> 04:06.370
interaction. It wasn't a question of money, as it 
is these days, because I was supported by a NASA

04:06.450 --> 04:12.760
traineeship. Was that your first contact with an 
ASA? Yes, basically it was.

04:23.297 --> 04:24.499
When did you finish your? I finished in late 1969. 
When you were a grad student at Stuart, did any of

04:28.242 --> 04:37.996
the infighting, well, or let's put it this way, 
Kuiper and Bart Bock were perhaps not the world's

04:28.242 --> 04:37.996
greatest friends? You know, I didn't really get 
too much feel from that. I mean, Bock came in 1967

04:43.404 --> 04:49.272
after I'd been there a couple of years. He was 
always telling stories about Kuiper and Bach, and

04:50.062 --> 05:00.117
I don't know, there was another guy, another 
Dutchman that came over to the U.S. about the same

04:50.062 --> 05:00.117
time as those two, and I can't remember. I think it 
was a guy,

05:01.038 --> 05:10.232
Peter Vandekamp, was it? No, but it's in Ray 
White's obituary at Bach, so we can look at it.

05:13.877 --> 05:15.580
Yeah, yeah, it's kind of neat, yeah. Did people at 
Stuart or Kitt Peak look down on planetary work as

05:16.100 --> 05:24.872
far as you know? Did the grad students say, oh, if I 
can't get in with somebody that does stellar work,

05:24.932 --> 05:30.841
I'll have to do planetary? Was any of that kind of 
stuff still left when you were there? I don't think

05:36.409 --> 05:36.989
so. Now that I think of it, yeah. Being a graduate 
student at Stuart was an interesting experience

05:40.147 --> 05:47.401
because you had a lunar and planetary lab right 
across the street. And the people that did

05:49.204 --> 06:00.265
planetary science, like Tom Garrels, like Pat 
Romer,

06:01.797 --> 06:08.629
I can't think of a few more names that were 
associated with a lunar and planetary

06:01.797 --> 06:08.629
observatory. They were there, yeah, exactly. And 
I never got the feeling that this was a

06:10.572 --> 06:17.925
secondary science. There was Bill Hartman, for 
example. He was there. I mean, it was interesting

06:20.289 --> 06:21.512
stuff. It just so happened that you know, you 
really do have a difference of opinion as to

06:23.482 --> 06:30.493
whether you want to go into planetary science. I 
mean, planetary science is almost like geology.

06:32.275 --> 06:34.419
It's close to home. And at least that was my 
feeling. I didn't want to get into planetary

06:35.701 --> 06:39.687
science, and I knew other graduate students that 
really didn't want to get into planetary science.

06:39.707 --> 06:41.530
They were more interested in stars and galaxies. 
And that's just sort of a natural, because there

06:42.591 --> 06:51.565
were graduate students, as a matter of fact, Ben 
Zellner, who's now, I guess he does asteroid work

06:53.333 --> 07:03.583
with , there was , there was a few other graduate 
students. Planetary science was a real

07:04.583 --> 07:07.426
challenge. It just wasn't something that I wanted 
to get into. Where'd you go after you got your

07:10.109 --> 07:13.912
degree? In January of 1970, we packed our bags, put 
our car on a boat, got on an airplane, and went to

07:22.882 --> 07:23.883
Chile.

07:26.647 --> 07:39.186
I became a staff member at the European Southern 
Observatory,

07:26.647 --> 07:39.186
primarily because Westerland, my thesis advisor 
six months earlier, had become the director

07:26.647 --> 07:39.186
there, and he said, Bob, why don't you come down for 
a year? So I said, fine, a year, I'll go anywhere.

07:42.090 --> 07:43.011
Ended up being settled. What did you work on there 
in general? In general, I was a staff astronomer,

07:46.757 --> 07:51.724
of course, and I had to assist him. all the 
equipment for all the visiting astronomers in

07:52.261 --> 08:00.293
terms of Kude spectrographs, Castorine 
spectrographs, single channel photometers and

07:52.261 --> 08:00.293
so on. And I continued my interest in OB 
associations and started surveying some of the

08:01.115 --> 08:20.985
southern Milky Way in terms of accumulating data 
that would allow us to then determine whether or

08:01.115 --> 08:20.985
not the young blue stars we were detecting were 
actually members of associations or whether they

08:01.115 --> 08:20.985
were just in the field. And when did you leave there 
and why? I left there in May of 1977, and we'd been in

08:24.882 --> 08:42.843
Chile seven years, and our daughters were then one 
and four years, so we decided to come back to the

08:24.882 --> 08:42.843
States, and we didn't want our kids growing up 
Chilean, basically. And the position I got in the

08:44.005 --> 08:50.753
U.S. was as a lecturer at the University of 
Virginia in Charlottesville. And I found it very

08:51.745 --> 08:59.496
difficult to look for a position from outside the 
US to get back into the US. And so I was very grateful

08:59.516 --> 09:07.308
to be able to get some kind of temporary position 
from which I could use as a base to look for a more

08:59.516 --> 09:07.308
permanent position. And that fell into place, 
unfortunately, upon the death of Nelson

09:07.328 --> 09:16.020
Lindbergh. This is D. Nelson Lindbergh. D. Nelson 
Lindbergh, exactly. And so what was this

09:19.225 --> 09:20.807
permanent place? Well, the position I got was 
University of Virginia as lecturer. And I was

09:25.561 --> 09:29.885
actually on the staff there for two years. And at 
the end of the second year, which would be 1979, in

09:29.905 --> 09:49.022
the middle 19s after academic year, 78, 79, I then 
took up a position at the National Radio Astronomy

09:29.905 --> 09:49.022
Observatory, more of an administrative position 
as assistant to the director with Mark Roberts. At

09:49.880 --> 09:59.815
that point, it was better not to have to move the 
family than to go to Washington, D.C. or someplace

09:49.880 --> 09:59.815
like that. Why did they pick you? I was a warm body. 
No, Mort Roberts and I got along very well. I had

10:06.726 --> 10:13.837
worked earlier as a summer student at NRAO in 1964 
in Green Bank with Mort. And I was interested in

10:14.658 --> 10:16.461
a... in an administrative position because I had 
been interviewed. Actually, I had been offered a

10:20.245 --> 10:25.332
job at the National Science Foundation by Bill 
Howard. And so I was trying to decide, did I want to

10:25.352 --> 10:30.660
leave Charlottesville and move to Washington or 
what? And Mort had just taken up position as

10:30.680 --> 10:37.489
director at NRAO about six months earlier, and he 
realized that he needed help. So for me, it was a new

10:38.251 --> 10:41.195
challenge I was happy to move into. How long did you 
stay there? Oh, I was with the NRAO, actually,

10:44.015 --> 10:48.599
until just the beginning of this year. I was in 
Charlottesville until mid-1988. So that's 11

10:52.683 --> 10:58.268
years in Charlottesville and an additional four 
years in Socorro. At the VLA. At the VLA, right.

11:03.212 --> 11:12.520
When you first went into the National Radio 
Astronomy Observatory, did you notice any

11:03.212 --> 11:12.520
difference between optical and radio 
astronomers? As a matter of fact, I did. I've

11:16.111 --> 11:19.574
always noticed the difference between optical 
and radio astronomers. You want to know what that

11:20.695 --> 11:21.776
difference is? Yes, you mean going back to grad 
school days? Yeah, basically. I mean, in grad

11:26.100 --> 11:30.144
school, I have to admit that I never really came 
across that many radio astronomers. Oh, there was

11:30.204 --> 11:36.711
Frank Lowe, and there was the odd, I mean... Rare. 
The rare radio astronomer that would come

11:36.891 --> 11:40.194
through. We did have one radio astronomer on the 
staff one official quote-unquote radio

11:43.837 --> 11:49.622
astronomer on the staff at the University of 
Arizona, and that was Andrei Paholchek. And he

11:50.663 --> 12:04.375
taught the course in radio astronomy, and I found 
radio astronomy to be much, much greater, much

11:50.663 --> 12:04.375
more intensity in real physics. That is, radio 
astronomers seem much more solidly based and

12:04.395 --> 12:12.342
solidly ground, if you will, in... in techniques 
and a theory of physics. The frustration, of

12:16.870 --> 12:23.099
course, with the radio astronomers, I found, of 
course, was that they didn't have any good angular

12:16.870 --> 12:23.099
resolution. They had instrumentation that they 
had to be extremely careful with. It seemed to me

12:26.224 --> 12:35.918
that radio astronomers knew a lot more about the 
inner workings of the computer than optical. I

12:36.018 --> 12:37.140
can't take that back. Optical astronomers 
generally knew a lot about their spectrographs.

12:41.245 --> 12:44.608
their polarimeters and photometers, because 
they had to make it work. Radio astronomers,

12:45.169 --> 12:56.039
however, had found the nice technique of relying 
upon a really high-quality staff of radio

12:45.169 --> 12:56.039
engineers and computer scientists. And so the 
actual astronomers really didn't know that much

12:56.079 --> 13:06.909
about the black boxes they were using, but the 
people that did made everything work exceedingly

12:56.079 --> 13:06.909
well. And at the NRIO, I noticed that most of the 
radio astronomers that I dealt with hardly ever

13:10.709 --> 13:16.718
would, they sort of looked down upon optical 
astronomy. They didn't care really what a

13:16.758 --> 13:22.327
spectral type was or what constellation or 
anything like that. They were really retooled

13:22.347 --> 13:29.398
physicists or retooled ham radio operators more 
than anything. Whereas optical astronomers

13:29.898 --> 13:37.510
tended to be types that got excited about 
astronomy from hands-on observing experiences

13:38.249 --> 13:41.372
when they were either in high school or college. 
And there was a rare optical astronomer who got

13:42.072 --> 13:53.482
into optical astronomy because they were good in 
physics and they were good in theory and then got

13:42.072 --> 13:53.482
pushed into optical astronomy. But in general, I 
thought the problems that radio astronomers were

13:53.523 --> 14:07.615
asking and were able to answer were a lot more 
in-depth in physics and global problems than

13:53.523 --> 14:07.615
optical astronomers were asking. Maybe that was 
naive, but that's my impression. Okay, so this

14:10.207 --> 14:17.997
year, early this year, I guess, you left Socorro, 
and where did you go? I left the, actually I left the

14:18.017 --> 14:28.991
NRAO, and I left Socorro both at the same time, and 
I'm now Executive Director of the Astronomical

14:18.017 --> 14:28.991
Society of the Pacific. And for me it's an ideal 
position because You know, I've sort of been a

14:32.418 --> 14:35.543
hybrid between optical and radio astronomy. I've 
never really put my solid foot down and said, this

14:35.583 --> 14:43.254
is my area, and I am pigeonholed forever. I just 
really get excited about all problems in

14:43.275 --> 14:53.350
astronomy, and I've always been involved with 
public outreach and public information since

14:43.275 --> 14:53.350
coming back to the NRAO. When I was in Chile, of 
course, I was working hand in in glove with all the

14:58.085 --> 15:00.068
visiting astronomers. So I got to see a broad 
perspective of the type of problems that

15:00.088 --> 15:05.777
everybody that came to the observatory was 
working on. And then when I came back to the U.S., I

15:06.478 --> 15:10.365
was involved with radio astronomy. So then I got a 
perspective of what it is to, what it means to be a

15:10.385 --> 15:21.342
millimeter wave astronomer or a centimeter wave 
astronomer or even a long wave astronomer and what

15:10.385 --> 15:21.342
the problems of resolution are and and different 
wavelength approaches to different problems.

15:25.708 --> 15:35.719
And so I found myself, you know, with quite a large 
global perspective that I guess I'm really now

15:25.708 --> 15:35.719
able to take advantage of in my dealings with the 
astronomical community. Why did you make this

15:36.100 --> 15:37.261
last jump? Was it because the opportunity was 
there? Basically, it was the opportunity was

15:39.704 --> 15:41.606
there. You know, Andy Fracknoy had been the 
executive director of the Astronomical Society

15:41.646 --> 15:49.075
of the Pacific for the last 14 years or so. And... I 
saw the advertisement in one of the, I think it was

15:51.410 --> 15:58.277
the AAS's job newsletter. I read the description, 
you know, it must be this, it must be that, and

15:59.078 --> 16:04.083
experience of this, experience of that. I said, 
you know, this is a job I can do. I can do all that

16:07.786 --> 16:09.028
stuff. I almost replied to that myself, and that 
would have been some competition, except that

16:09.388 --> 16:17.796
this NASA contract was already looking good. I 
see, I see. We already had word that we got it. And

16:22.780 --> 16:29.669
also, I have to add that it was more or less an 
opportunity for me to be my own boss, as it were.

16:29.869 --> 16:38.481
It's kind of hard to work year after year after 
year, sometimes having ideas that your boss

16:29.869 --> 16:38.481
doesn't necessarily share, enthusiasm, 
support, and so on. And now, in this position, I can

16:39.121 --> 16:42.766
sort of make it or break it. I can pave new ground if I 
really get enough energy up to do it. So you've done

16:48.654 --> 16:51.758
optical, you've done radio, and now you have... I 
have to do everything. I have to do everything.

16:54.272 --> 16:58.437
Which is one of the reasons I want to interview, 
because I'm going to start asking you some

16:54.272 --> 16:58.437
questions now today.

