26:05.565 --> 26:15.177
in the surface. Do you think that's had any effect 
on the public? I mean, has it changed the way they

26:17.460 --> 26:24.248
look at things or their interests in planetary 
astronomy, astronomy and science in general? Or

26:24.268 --> 26:25.930
is it a passing fact? You know, I think we have to be 
careful to answer a question like that because I

26:28.272 --> 26:49.103
think that the space program in general and also 
the

26:28.272 --> 26:49.103
detailed information that comes from the space 
probes about other planets in the solar system has

26:28.272 --> 26:49.103
made the public almost take things for granted. I 
remember when I was in high school or when you were

26:50.365 --> 26:53.149
in school, You know, one space probe, one space 
launch was a fantastic event. Nowadays, we have

26:58.932 --> 27:03.576
shuttles get set up every month or two, and no big 
deal. We don't go through the countdown. We don't

27:05.298 --> 27:07.059
hear anything in the news. You know, we know 
they're up there. We take it for granted that

27:08.641 --> 27:10.603
they're doing good stuff. And another space probe 
goes by. I mean, Voyager was a big deal, no doubt

27:13.265 --> 27:15.267
about it. But, you know, does the public get 
excited about another telescope getting

27:17.549 --> 27:20.892
launched? Astronomers make lots of noise about 
it. And the amount of information that comes from

27:22.965 --> 27:28.990
that new telescope can be overwhelming. There's 
just so much data coming down. But the public is

27:31.733 --> 27:41.062
sort of getting

27:31.733 --> 27:41.062
blase about the whole thing and taking things for 
granted. Here's a question you don't have to be a

27:41.342 --> 27:44.425
planetary astronomer to answer. But you have to 
know something about astronomy and the funding

27:44.465 --> 27:50.271
end and all that. and the public interest in. In 30 
years now, we've looked all over the solar system,

27:51.645 --> 28:03.419
haven't yet found a trace of present or previous 
life anywhere except Earth. In particular, no

28:03.439 --> 28:06.443
green men on Mars, not even a bug. Sure. Do you think 
that's had a negative effect on public interest

28:07.524 --> 28:11.349
funding or not? No, I don't think so. I really don't 
think so. Why don't I think so? That's a good

28:18.277 --> 28:19.178
question. I mean, I think the search is fun. And the 
questions always come down from the press or from

28:23.172 --> 28:29.922
people that don't know a lot of details about the 
types of search and so on. Have you found it? Part of

28:32.966 --> 28:44.743
the problem that the scientist has in 
communicating science to the public

28:45.635 --> 28:55.568
is related to their desire to know the biggest or 
the smallest, the most distant or the closest, the

28:45.635 --> 28:55.568
oldest or the youngest, or what's the latest 
discovery. I mean, they think science is made up of

28:55.588 --> 29:04.560
just eureka discoveries, and they don't really 
understand the scientific curiosity process. So

29:06.382 --> 29:08.905
I think there's an interest, you know, in the 
public. If you say that you're looking for

29:09.086 --> 29:14.072
extraterrestrial intelligence or you're 
looking for life in the solar system, And that's

29:14.322 --> 29:17.086
always a motivation to get the public interested. 
They're always going to ask you, did you find it?

29:19.910 --> 29:39.317
But

29:19.910 --> 29:39.317
part of the challenge of being a scientist is to 
give

29:19.910 --> 29:39.317
the public more appreciation for the fact that 
it's the hunt that's most important. It's the

29:39.820 --> 29:43.546
thrill of the hunt, and that continues no matter 
what you find. You open more unanswered doors than

29:44.107 --> 29:54.725
you do, you know, you always ask more questions 
after you've made an experiment than you answer.

29:54.805 --> 29:55.586
It's just amazing. Here's a two-part question. 
One, do you think astronomers in general have done

29:57.289 --> 30:06.064
a good job, or as good a job as they could have been, 
in selling themselves to the public and to the

29:57.289 --> 30:06.064
Congress? And then I'm going to be specific and 
say, I believe that the radio astronomers have

30:08.069 --> 30:23.755
always done their infighting behind closed 
doors, spilled the blood there, and come out

30:08.069 --> 30:23.755
charging with a unified front, whereas the 
optical astronomers do all their internecine

30:08.069 --> 30:23.755
strife on the stage. So Perot, Kahn, what do you 
think? Getting astronomers, or getting

30:29.146 --> 30:45.808
scientists in general, but the scientists I know 
best are astronomers, and getting astronomers to

30:29.146 --> 30:45.808
be forthright and to participate in public 
outreach programs is a mixed bag. There's about, I

30:45.848 --> 30:54.580
would say, like 10% of the astronomers on the staff 
of major research facilities that are really

30:45.848 --> 30:54.580
willing to be science for judges or to give tours to 
observatories and so on. I think it's a lot

31:00.632 --> 31:10.105
different when you get to the academic community 
because their people are constantly dealing with

31:00.632 --> 31:10.105
students and the public and so the percentage 
there probably is much higher. I think and on that

31:12.308 --> 31:20.179
basis I would say astronomers really haven't done 
a good job but I mean how many astronomers do you

31:12.308 --> 31:20.179
need to have out there One Carl Sagan is worth 
10,000 other astronomers. And so it's kind of hard

31:25.826 --> 31:27.789
to answer that question. Now, related to the 
question of optical versus radio, I think you have

31:27.809 --> 31:33.797
to be very, very careful.

31:35.360 --> 31:49.339
Because radio astronomers have always been 
really totally dependent very soon after the

31:35.360 --> 31:49.339
beginning of radio astronomy. Radio astronomy 
actually began in the 1930s and really wasn't

31:49.859 --> 31:57.409
going full force until the 1950s after the war. And 
very soon thereafter was the creation of national

31:57.630 --> 32:01.935
observatories. So radio astronomers have 
always, not always, but for the most part, have

32:01.955 --> 32:10.627
been using national facilities. You just know 
they cannot spend the money at a local university

32:10.788 --> 32:17.757
to build an instrument big enough, so it's been 
national facilities. And it's a much smaller

32:18.142 --> 32:27.434
population of scientists, let's say probably 
between 10% and 20% of the number of optical

32:18.142 --> 32:27.434
astronomers. And so the people to do the fighting 
are fewer. The efficiency of getting telescope

32:33.762 --> 32:45.617
time for the members of the community because of 
the existence of large national centers like

32:33.762 --> 32:45.617
Arecibo and NRAO and so on, and some major 
university facilities like Owens Valley and so

32:46.205 --> 32:51.131
on. It's much more successful for radio 
astronomers to get telescope time. Optical

32:58.019 --> 33:02.804
astronomers, on the other hand, they come from a 
different community at the outset.

33:03.325 --> 33:13.057
Historically, they grew up in large private 
telescopes like Lick and Mount Palomar and so on.

33:13.097 --> 33:15.199
And so they were in-house type astronomers. And 
only over the course of the last three

33:15.685 --> 33:29.706
decades, so to speak, since the NSF was founded, 
have you gotten astronomers spread out far and

33:15.685 --> 33:29.706
wide at small schools and large schools and 
everywhere. And they don't have their own

33:29.726 --> 33:32.851
telescopes. And so there's the in-group, the 
people that have their own private, as it were,

33:32.871 --> 33:44.629
major facility, University of Texas, Caltech, 
Those big places, Arizona and so on, and those

33:45.335 --> 33:54.165
people are sort of the upper cream, the best 
scientists there always have lots of telescope

33:45.335 --> 33:54.165
time. And you've got the other community out there 
fighting for telescope time because they don't

33:54.686 --> 34:00.974
have their own telescopes that are there. It seems 
to be a much, for one thing it's a much larger

34:03.076 --> 34:08.963
community, I'd like to say before probably a 
factor of 10 higher. and there's not enough

34:09.685 --> 34:19.078
national facility telescope time to go around for 
this large mass of scientists that are groping for

34:09.685 --> 34:19.078
time. So they tend probably, you know, when it 
comes right down to it, it's easy to say, you know,

34:19.478 --> 34:35.119
you iron your difficulties out in private, but 
there's always somebody that walks away feeling

34:19.478 --> 34:35.119
hurt whenever you have a discussion about whether 
planetary science is better than, extragalactic

34:35.453 --> 34:39.765
or ultraviolet is better than x-ray and so on. 
Somebody... In that connection, planetary

34:40.547 --> 34:44.177
astronomy is really half and half. It shares some 
characteristics with both. But what I'm thinking

34:46.062 --> 34:48.248
of, for example, a 10-year recommendation 
reports come together. The radio astronomers

34:50.270 --> 34:53.873
seem to pick one thing and stick with it. Planetary 
astronomers pick one thing and stick with it. And

34:56.475 --> 35:03.943
the stellar and galactic and extra-galactic 
optical astronomers keep right on fighting even

34:56.475 --> 35:03.943
after it comes out. It seems like it. It always 
seems that way. It does seem that way. But I can tell

35:06.885 --> 35:10.629
you that there's plenty of hurt people in the radio 
community, too. Although they came together and

35:10.729 --> 35:17.155
endorsed VLBA, back in the early 80s. And lo and 
behold, the darn thing is constructed now because

35:20.456 --> 35:28.286
it was a project that was ready to go when the 
funding became available. There are also a lot of

35:30.508 --> 35:37.177
hurt people in the radio community that were 
hoping for a 25-millimeter wave dish. It never

35:37.717 --> 35:38.438
happened. And the NRAO is ready to go with a 
millimeter array. I don't know if it'll ever

35:44.466 --> 35:45.707
happen. And gradually the astronomers at some of 
the major universities have started to build

35:46.177 --> 35:53.950
their own millimeter array. Millimeter 
astronomers have basically felt like they've

35:53.970 --> 35:58.719
been left off. And it's an extremely powerful 
field. Lately, a lot of astronomers, and we're

36:07.034 --> 36:30.258
talking optical, radio, planetary, stellar, 
have been getting a lot of publicity and evidently

36:07.034 --> 36:30.258
some money off of projects that get a lot of public 
play, like search for extraterrestrial

36:07.034 --> 36:30.258
intelligence, killer asteroids, search for 
other solar systems, ozone holes in the Earth's

36:07.034 --> 36:30.258
atmosphere. Do you think they're overdoing that 
or not? I think the public is extremely interested

36:34.042 --> 36:36.805
in these type of projects, and it's good that they 
get press. I think astronomers have to be careful

36:41.380 --> 36:54.433
to spread the press out to, and I think the AAS does a 
real good job, and Steve Moran in the press office,

36:41.380 --> 36:54.433
in getting the press interested in other ongoing 
critical issues in astronomy. You have to

36:54.473 --> 37:04.362
remember that some of those topics in modern 
astronomy are pretty esoteric and hard to

36:54.473 --> 37:04.362
describe to the public, so killer asteroids and 
SETI and all those you know planetary stuff that's

37:04.848 --> 37:24.628
when one respect planetary science has an 
advantage it's easier to communicate the problem

37:04.848 --> 37:24.628
to the public i don't think we can i don't think we 
can really overdo communicating the public

37:04.848 --> 37:24.628
however and what's good for planetary scientists 
in the short run because their project is

37:25.199 --> 37:28.363
described well to the press. It's good for 
astronomers in general. Whether it's planetary,

37:30.526 --> 37:35.293
radio, or optical, I think probably all in the same 
bathtub. I mean, all in the same boat. And is the

37:36.975 --> 37:40.260
boat sailing along nicely? Is it dead in the water? 
Or is it sinking in general as far as, say, funding

37:41.722 --> 37:53.097
goes and stuff like that?

37:53.347 --> 37:54.489
Well, I don't know. I have to be careful. Not 
necessarily just funding, because we know that's

37:55.850 --> 37:58.534
dead in the water. But what do you think? Use your 
crystal ball. I mean, I've always felt that

38:02.740 --> 38:13.114
we tend to get too greedy. We tend to get a major 
facility and then milk it to death for data. And

38:23.958 --> 38:25.039
we're never satisfied. There's another facility 
we just have to have, another facility we just have

38:25.059 --> 38:28.644
to have. And admittedly, it is a complex area 
because you always need more resolution. You

38:33.530 --> 38:35.172
always need a different wavelength coverage. And 
the problems nowadays are not simply focused in

38:35.712 --> 38:42.721
what you can get out of the ultraviolet data or what 
you can get out of the infrared data. You have to put

38:42.841 --> 38:46.405
the whole thing together in one big 
multi-wavelength picture. And astronomers know

38:46.655 --> 38:52.304
you need 20 telescopes and not just one. And 
Congress wonders, well, jeez, I just gave you one.

38:55.669 --> 38:59.154
Why do you need another one? But is the situation 
healthy? I think that in terms of our ability to do

39:03.581 --> 39:14.417
research, let's say the ability to gather the data 
that we need, the situation is extremely healthy.

39:14.937 --> 39:26.053
The question on an individual basis, for an 
individual, can an individual exist at a

39:14.937 --> 39:26.053
university or make a career, you know, there's a 
threat there. There's a threat there because the

39:26.073 --> 39:31.580
funding, the instruments are there, the data is 
there for the best people. The question is what

39:31.981 --> 39:35.526
about the middle pack? Is there enough funding to 
attract the brightest students into the field, to

39:39.811 --> 39:45.979
keep them into the field, and so on. And I think the 
situation there is of great concern. The number of

39:49.964 --> 39:56.753
PhDs that are generated is like a factor of three or 
four at least, more than the number of real jobs.

39:57.634 --> 39:58.655
And that's a concern. That's not healthy in the 
long term. On the other hand, should there be a

40:03.200 --> 40:14.893
continuous growth in the number of PhDs that are 
created in a field like astronomy, I think we have

40:03.200 --> 40:14.893
to reach a steady state. Otherwise, there won't be 
any archaeologists left, and there won't be any

40:14.913 --> 40:20.379
new farmers, and so on. I think one indicator of 
public interest and the public taxpayer's

40:20.739 --> 40:30.490
willingness to support, give money to astronomy, 
Are the fortunes of the Astronomical Society of

40:31.027 --> 40:37.299
the Pacific, how are those doing now? Well, the 
Astronomical Society of the Pacific has always

40:37.319 --> 40:47.678
had great success in its programs, primarily 
because it addresses issues in education.

40:48.400 --> 40:54.030
There's a vast pool of teachers out there that need 
help. and information on astronomy and the way to

40:54.584 --> 40:58.690
teach it to kids and so on. Teachers that have not 
had any formal training themselves and sometimes

40:58.751 --> 41:06.142
not even formal training in science. The ASP has 
extremely successful summer meetings that have

41:07.244 --> 41:22.448
just grown by leaps and bounds in communicating 
science in a very popular way and also addressing

41:07.244 --> 41:22.448
some professional scientific topics as well as 
teacher workshops and so on. The problem that the

41:23.069 --> 41:41.072
ASB has is one that most nonprofit societies face 
at one time or another, and that's the bottom line

41:23.069 --> 41:41.072
in terms of getting the funds it requires just to 
keep operating. I mean, it's a small society. Its

41:45.658 --> 41:51.726
historical base is regional.

41:53.056 --> 42:10.037
It's so broad that

41:53.056 --> 42:10.037
it has been hard in the recent past to actually 
attract funds, I guess, basically, in terms of

41:53.056 --> 42:10.037
there's no real strong corporate support. Those 
are some of the goals that I have in getting strong

42:12.020 --> 42:21.932
corporate support and getting the programs 
underwritten

42:22.486 --> 42:31.636
by funding agencies, people that are interested 
in education, and getting more professional

42:22.486 --> 42:31.636
involvement in the society.

42:35.921 --> 42:47.734
Some people join the society, and after a year or 
two, they realize that they come to the conclusion

42:35.921 --> 42:47.734
that they're not getting enough out of society to 
continue being members. And my answer to them is,

42:48.794 --> 42:52.337
hey, listen, the society is made up of you. You 
maybe don't have enough time to go out and talk to

42:53.158 --> 43:03.669
your local school classes or to give a public 
lecture and so on. But as a scientist, as an

43:04.109 --> 43:17.502
astronomer, you should give some strong support 
and backing to those people in the scientific

43:04.109 --> 43:17.502
community who are willing to do the outreach 
programs that you basically should be morally

43:18.241 --> 43:28.070
obligated to support because you're getting 
support from the public. And so you've got to give

43:28.130 --> 43:29.131
something back. Some people just don't like to do 
that. So why not join the society and let the

43:30.733 --> 43:36.458
society do it for them and speak strongly with one 
voice? So the society is in a great state of change

43:37.399 --> 43:47.488
right now in terms of expansion, in terms of 
seeking funding support, and in terms of the type

43:47.772 --> 43:58.390
of programs we want to get into, I have no doubt that 
we'll succeed in all this. This doesn't have

43:59.500 --> 44:02.785
anything to do with the history of planetary 
astronomy, but I've got to ask you. The very name,

44:04.006 --> 44:08.593
Astronaut of the Pacific, implies regional. We 
don't want to be just regional anymore. I'm

44:11.057 --> 44:13.780
thinking of changing the name. That question was 
put to me originally when I got interested in

44:14.201 --> 44:19.449
society. I looked at it and I said, yeah, you're 
right. The name is a detriment when somebody back

44:21.992 --> 44:26.098
in Georgia goes to their dean and says they're 
going to publish a paper in the PASP. He says, why

44:30.542 --> 44:32.004
the PASP? Why not the PASA? If there's such a 
journal. Or if you go to the University of Florida

44:38.773 --> 44:47.524
and say you want to have a meeting of the ASP in 
Florida, they're going to say, who's the ASP? But

44:50.581 --> 44:54.286
You have to remember the society is a real 
venerable society. It's been around for over 100

44:54.346 --> 44:56.089
years. There's a very strong following here on the 
West Coast and in several of the states in the U.S.

44:56.569 --> 45:07.264
And we even have members from 70 foreign 
countries. There are plenty of other

45:08.106 --> 45:11.951
organizations that exist with strange names. It 
just makes it a little bit more of a challenge, a

45:12.592 --> 45:16.217
little more of a challenge challenge to do our I 
don't really feel that it's a time to upset the

45:16.383 --> 45:26.187
apple cart by making a name change. A new director 
and a new name change? No, no, no. We'll exist with

45:29.956 --> 45:32.282
our own name, with our old name.

